Introduction
\layout Standard


\emph on 
The time has come, Van Haarlem said, to talk of many things
\emph default 
.
 And by golly, he is right! CS1 will be upon us soon, and CDR-II looms.
 This is the skeleton of an input document to the LOFAR CDR-II, in November
 2006.
 It is also meant as a framework to focus the discussion within the LOFAR
 Calibration StuurGrope (LCSG).
 This group, which has been assembled for the wrong reasons, will be seen
 as crucial by later generations.
 Since, unlike the WSRT, LOFAR is not being built by its eventual users,
 the LCSG, in all its limitations, must be regarded as a last ditch garantor
 of LOFAR performance.
 During its short tenure, the LCSG has already touched on many issues that
 should have been discussed, and acted upon, years ago.
 There is little point in this stage to ask why this has not happened.
 Our motto should be 'better late than never'.
 But we should get on with it.
\layout Standard

After some preliminaries, the first part of this document contains (an attempt
 to develop) a framework for estimating dynamic range, in which each calibration
 effect can be quantified, and placed in some order of seriousness.
 The second part is (the start of) a full list of the factors that will
 affect, and potentially limit, LOFAR calibration, and thus the quality
 of its results.
 All of them have been discussed before, but it is useful to have them all
 together in one place.
 
\layout Standard

It is essential for credibility that the finished CDR-II document is fully
 understood, and supported, by the extended LCSG, i.e.
 including the small group of 'other aperture synthesis experts' that is
 occasionally invited.
 Therefore, the early versions will be peppered with undiplomatic remarks
 designed to grab the attention.
 These will be gradually removed in consecutive versions, after which the
 early ones will just be highly valued collectors' items.
