\layout Section

A framework for estimating dynamic range
\layout Standard

This section is the real meat of this document.
 AGB
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{AGB-JEN}

\end_inset 

 has analysed the requiements, and concluded that it is acceptable if LOFAR
 standard calibration yields residual images with an average dynamic range
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{4}$
\end_inset 

 (somewhat less for those fields that have very bright sources in them).
 He also produced a list of instrumental effects, with their expected magnitudes.
 The challenge is to develop a general frame-work in which each effect can
 be quantified, and placed in some order of seriousness.
 Three approaches will be treated here.
 
\layout Subsection

Snapshot approach (JDB)
\layout Subsection

Image-plane approach (AGB)
\layout Subsection

uv-plane approach (JEN)
\layout Standard

Most instrumental effects occur in the uv-plane, in the sense that they
 affect (subsets of) uv-data in some way.
 This will be translated into a convolution in the image, i.e.
 each source in the field will be 'multiplied' with an error-pattern which
 varies slowly over the field.
 The pattern will be related to the uv-coverage of the affected subset of
 uv-data.
 For dynamic range calculations, we may concentrate on the pattern around
 the brightest source.
 Thus, the analysis is independent of the source distribution (a considerable
 advantage).
\layout Standard

The purpose of calibration is to produce residual images that are as empty
 as possible.
 They are made from residual uv-data, which are obtained by subtracting
 predicted values from the measured uv-data, and correcting them for the
 image centre.
 In the absence of systematic effects, the uv-residuals will be noise-like
 (gaussian?), resulting in images with a simularly noisy mien.
 But if a subset of uv-residuals shares a common error, e.g.
 an amplitude offset or a phase gradient, this will produce a convolution
 pattern with a well-defined rms sidelobe level around the brightest source
 in the image.
 Other effects, affecting different subsets of uv-residuals, will cause
 different convolution patterns.
 If these patterns are sufficiently different, the total rms sidelobe level
 will increase as the square root of the patterns.
\layout Standard

Sines and cosines....?
\layout Standard

So, the problem is reduced to listing subsets of uv-residuals, and whether
 they share an offset or a phase gradient.
 Or in other words, listing the correlation footprint of each effect in
 the uv-plane.
 For instance:
\layout Itemize

An ionosphere error will produce a phase gradient over the entire array,
 i.e.
 all uv-residuals, but correlated over a limited time (e.g.
 10 minutes).
 Thus the total rms error level is the square root of the number of 10-minute
 slots, multiplied by the sidelobe level (in the image) of a single one.
\layout Itemize

A station gain error will produce an amplitude offset over the subset of
 uv-residuals that shares that station, but it will be correlated over a
 substantial time (an hour?).
\layout Itemize

A station pointing error will produce a phase gradient (?) over its subset
 of uv-residuals.
\layout Itemize

An ifr-based error can only be dealt with if it is constant over the entire
 observation.
 
\layout Itemize

The BSR effect, .....
\layout Standard

You get the idea.
 I need some help from people like Jaap to derive the correct summing expression
s.
 Especially in those cases where the subsets overlap, like in station-based
 effects.
 It should be interesting to calculate the relative impact on the dynamic
 range of the same effect, but for different correlation periods....
\layout Section

LOFAR Calibration flow diagram
\layout Standard

This document is not a description of LOFAR calibration.
 Rather, it is assumed that the reader is thoroughly familiar with various
 earlier documents, especially the Calibration Strategy
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{JEN-nov2005}

\end_inset 

 presented at CDR-I in November 2005.
 After all, I did not sacrifice half my Indian trip just to pad some paper
 trail.
 However, just to jolt the memory and set the scene, some points will be
 repeated (and thus emphasized) here:
\layout Itemize

Calibration is defined as the capability to subtract foreground sources.
 The goal is to produce residual images that are as empty as possible.
\layout Itemize

Only the brightest (Cat I) sources are used for selfcal, i.e.
 to estimate instrumental errors.
 The parameters of these sources may also be estimated in this process.
 
\layout Itemize

Cat II sources are detected and updated in residual images.
 Most of them are too faint for selfcal and in any case there are far too
 many of them.
 However, they still have to be subtracted from the uv-data, which might
 well prove to be the bottleneck of LOFAR calibration.
\layout Itemize

Cat I sources are subtracted with their 'private' instrumental parameters,
 for highest possible accuracy.
 Cat II sources are subtracted with interpolated values of MIM and beamshape
 functions.
\layout Itemize

Unproven thesis: Any source that is bright enough to cause trouble, is bright
 enough to be tackled.
\layout Itemize

The process of alternating between uv-data and residual images is called
 the Major Cycle.
 The Local Sky Model (LSM) is a key element of this process.
\layout Standard

The standard procedure (used for Survey mode) has the following steps:
\layout Enumerate

Generate a Local Sky Model (LSM).
 Use the observational windows of the observation (primary beam, spectral
 window) to select relevant sources from the Global Sky Model (GSM).
 The LSM includes all source in the main lobe of the primary beam, and a
 small number of very bright sources (the A-team) all over the sky.
\layout Enumerate

Find ionospheric phase lock: 
\layout Enumerate

Ionospheric phase tracking: Keep the ionospheric phase errors within a radian,
 by solving for the linear component of the MIM.
 Use one or more bright calibrators in the field.
\layout Enumerate

Bandpass removal: Divide out the high-granularity (channel-by-channel) IF
 bandpasses, determined (somehow) at station level.
 
\layout Enumerate

Coarse flagging:
\layout Enumerate

All the following is part of the Major Cycle: Selfcal, LSM subtraction,
 facet imaging, LSM update from residual imaging.
\layout Enumerate

Selfcal, i.e.
 solving for M.E.
 parameters, is done in peeling mode: we deal with Cat I sources in descending
 order of brightness, and subtract them from the uv-data before moving on
 to the next one.
 The phase centre of the uv-data is moved to the position of the peeling
 source.
 See also section ...
 
\layout Enumerate

Solving for large-scale smooth functions (l,m):
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

MIM refinement: Solve for (improvements of) the higher order component of
 the MIM.
 Use longer integration on a number of fainter calibrator sources on the
 field.
\layout Enumerate

Beamshape determination:
\end_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

Subtraction of Cat II sources (Cat I sources are subtracted as part of the
 peeling selfcal above).
 Patches, uvbricks.
 
\layout Enumerate

Facet imaging.
 The size of a facet is determined by the ionosphere.
 For each facet, the residual uv-data are corrected for the facet centre,
 after which the phase centre is shifted to that position, and the FOV is
 reduced by integrating over freq and time.
 The results are gridded and Fourier Transformed to a set of 4D residual
 images (which may overlap a little).
 
\layout Enumerate

Source extraction.
 The 4D residual images are deconvolved (e.g.
 CLEANed), using a PSF which strictly is valid for the facet centre only.
 The resulting images of CLEAN components are used for source extraction
 in two ways: 
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

Updating the parameters of existing LSM sources.
 The LSM is used to inspect the areas where Cat I/II sources have been subtracte
d to see whether there is anything left.
 Any residuals are used to solve for improvements of the source parameters,
 using the source trees in the LSM.
\layout Enumerate

Finding new LSM sources.
 The most difficult problem is to decide which groups of CLEAN components
 represent new (Cat III) sources, and how they should be parametrized.
 Extended sources may be modeled in terms of base functions like shapelets
 or pixons.
 Really pathological sources may be stored in the LSM as 4D images.
 
\end_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

The Major Cycle is repeated until some calibration quality criterion is
 met.
 At least two cycles will be needed to reach a dynamic range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1:10^{4}$
\end_inset 

, as required in the survey mode.
 
\layout Enumerate

Finishing touches:
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

Update the Global Sky Model (GSM) from the LSM.
 
\layout Enumerate

Make images from the LSM sources, to be used by Surveys KSG 
\layout Enumerate

Deliver the deliverables (residual images, [LSM] or images, [GSM], [MeqParm
 tables], [metadata])
\end_deeper 
