\layout Subsection

The effects of mutual coupling and the ground plane
\layout Standard

Statement: It has become clear that our intuitive understanding of station
 beamforming is insufficient, and that the unkown effects are significant.
 We may probably (?) assume that the instantaneous, monochromatic beam must
 be smooth, because of the properties of the FT (the elements are close
 together).
 However, the beamshape might be very unsmooth in frequency, and in time
 as a field is being tracked.
 For all these reasons, reliable simulations are urgently required before
 expensive decisions are taken.
\layout Standard

The situation is that a full E-M simulation Matlab program exists, although
 its veracity has not yet been fully verified.
 However, it is slow, and cannot simulate an entire HBA station.
 It is possible (according to Rob Maaskant) that these limitations can be
 rectified within the next 3 months, but that at the very least requires
 the will to do it
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed true

\layout Standard

There is another E-M simulation program that could be run on the Blue Gene,
 but that does not appear to be suitable for our particular problem.
 
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

In the meantime, Stefan Wijnholds has made a valiant attempt to demonstrate
 the magnitude of the effect with the help of a simple model, with and without
 mutual coupling.
 Having done that succesfully, he tried to augment his model to get a result
 that resembled the full E-M simulation (24 hrs) of the same station configurati
on.
 Since his program is fast (1 s), this would give us the means for rapid
 experimentation, which would be verified agains the full simulation from
 time to time.
 This approach has not yet been succesful.
 Perhaps Thomas Wilhelmson can help (he understands surface waves).
 
\layout Subsection

Far sidelobes
\layout Standard

It is necessary to measure and subtract the 'A-team' of 3-5 brightest sources
 at all times.
 We should be prepared for rapid gain (and phase!) variations, as the beam
 pattern rotates around the pointing centre.
 But there is absolutely no prospect of estimating the shape of the sidelobes
 for the purpose of subtracting fainter sources (especially very extended
 ones!).
 Therefore, it is essential that the side-lobe patterns of the various stations
 are as uniform as possible (i.e.
 no high peaks), and as different from each other as possible.
 This is achieved for the LBA array by having 'random logarithmic' station
 element configurations.
 In this way, the contaminating influence of far-out sources on the selfcal
 solution will be minimised.
 And their images (and sidelobes) in the residual image will be minimised.
 Especially if we use a wide bandwidth for both selfcal and imaging.
 
\layout Standard

NB: One of the conclusions of Wijnholds 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wijholds-core}

\end_inset 

 is that LBA stations should be random, but all identical.
 The idea is that, just like with the WSRT, it takes time to measure the
 various beamshapes, and it is better to do this only once.
 I
\emph on 
 beg to differ...
\emph default 
.
\layout Section

IF bandpass: BJones(f,t)
\layout Standard

The BJones is defined as a uv-plane effect, i.e.
 it is valid for all sources in the FOV (main lobe).
 Any position-dependent differences are due to the beamshapes etc.
 
\layout Standard

High granularity (channel-to-channel) complex gain variations are assumed
 to be due to the electronics.
 These should be measured at station level, and divided out near the correlator.
 The calibration system solves for slow variations (f,t) only, using the
 known spectrum of celestial sources.
 This process is influenced by the station beamshapes EJones(f,t).
\layout Section

Polarization calibration
\layout Standard

Instrumental polarization is caused by differences between X and Y voltage
 beams.
 These will be rather large for LOFAR.
 Even though we will be able to estimate the voltage beams quite accurately,
 some of the parameters are fundamentally out of reach 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{JPH-IV}

\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, a potential problem for calibration is the dearth of bright
 polarized sources at LOFAR frequencies (msec pulsars only?).
 However, we might use large-scale constraints (V=0, <Q>=0, <U>=0), and
 perhaps even the foreground polarization discovered with the WSRT.
\layout Section

