Peeling
\layout Standard

In principle, it is possible to make a large simultaneous solution for the
 instrumental parameters in the direction of all bright sources.
 Since this is rather expensive, peeling was invented 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{JEN-peeling}

\end_inset 

.
 The idea is to deal with Cat I sources in order of decreasing brightness,
 treating each of them as if they are the only source in the sky.
 After solving for instrumental parameters in its direction, its contribution
 is subtracted (peeled) from the uv-data before moving to the next brightest
 source.
 The greatest advantage is obtained by moving the phase centre of the uv-data
 to the position of the peeling source.
 Since the latter is in the phase centre, its visibility function will only
 vary slowly over the solution domain, and will thus be approximately linear
 over large domain cells.
 This allows a significant reduction in the number of cells for which the
 source must be predicted, to be repeated for each iteration.
 
\layout Standard

Unfortunately, the 'contamination' by other (fainter) sources will have
 an effect on the selfcal solution which probably cannot be ignored.
 The good news is that this contamination may be reduced to arbitrary levels
 by taking enough of the fainter sources into account.
 Since this is expensive, it must be reduced (dunamically) to a minimum.
