Facet imaging
\layout Standard

Uv-data can only be corrected for a single point in the sky, usually the
 centre of the field.
 Residual errors will increase with distance to this point, i.e.
 the (known) PSF for the field centre will become less valid towards the
 edge.
 Thus, it will be more difficult to deconvolve the non-LSM sources (Cat
 III) that have not been subtracted from the uv-data.
 This problem may be minimised by making multiple small 'facet' images to
 tile the FOV.
 For each, the phase centre of the residual uv-data are shifted to its centre,
 and corrected for that position.
 Then the FOV is reduced by integration over (f,t).
 
